==Abstract==

This IIP ensures INTcoin has a finite monetary supply by properly handling subsidy calculations to avoid overflow or wrap-around after many halvings.

==Motivation==

The block subsidy halving formula, if implemented naively, could cause integer overflow or unexpected behavior after 64+ halvings. This IIP ensures the supply converges to a fixed maximum.

==Specification==

===Maximum Supply===

<pre>
Total supply: 221,000,000,000 INT (221 billion)
MAX_MONEY = 221,000,000,0000,0000 (in base units)
</pre>

===Subsidy Schedule===

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Era !! Block Range !! Subsidy (INT) !! Cumulative Supply
|-
| 1 || 0 - 525,599 || 200,000 || ~105.1B
|-
| 2 || 525,600 - 1,051,199 || 100,000 || ~157.7B
|-
| 3 || 1,051,200 - 1,576,799 || 50,000 || ~184.0B
|-
| 4 || 1,576,800 - 2,102,399 || 25,000 || ~197.1B
|-
| ... || ... || ... || ...
|-
| ∞ || After ~64 halvings || 0 || 221B (max)
|}

===Halving Interval===

<pre>
nSubsidyHalvingInterval = 525,600 blocks (~1 year at 1-minute blocks)
</pre>

===Subsidy Calculation===

<pre>
CAmount GetBlockSubsidy(int nHeight, const Consensus::Params& params) {
    int halvings = nHeight / params.nSubsidyHalvingInterval;

    // After 64 halvings, subsidy is 0 (shift >= 64 bits)
    if (halvings >= 64) {
        return 0;
    }

    CAmount nSubsidy = params.nInitialSubsidy;
    nSubsidy >>= halvings;

    return nSubsidy;
}
</pre>

===INTcoin vs Bitcoin===

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Parameter !! INTcoin !! Bitcoin
|-
| Max Supply || 221 billion || 21 million
|-
| Initial Subsidy || 200,000 INT || 50 BTC
|-
| Halving Interval || 525,600 blocks || 210,000 blocks
|-
| Block Time || 1 minute || 10 minutes
|-
| Decimal Places || 4 || 8
|}

===COIN Constant===

<pre>
COIN = 10,000 (4 decimal places)
</pre>

==Security Considerations==

All arithmetic involving monetary amounts must:
# Check MoneyRange() before operations
# Use safe addition that checks for overflow
# Reject blocks with invalid coinbase values

